= Conclusion

This paper addressed the AI security dilemma by combining red teaming and blue teaming into one operational model. Red teaming identified realistic ways to break LLM-based systems, while blue teaming translated those findings into layered and measurable controls.

The resulting TSLL architecture provides a practical path for organizations: continuously test, harden, monitor, and improve. Rather than treating AI security as a static checklist, the paper frames it as an iterative engineering discipline grounded in evidence and risk reduction.

Future work should validate the model empirically across sectors and system types, with standardized datasets and benchmarks for adversarial AI security evaluation.

In this sense, the paper contributes a design-science style artifact that links technical security practice with governance and audit expectations in a unified, operational framework @nist_sp800_53a_2022 @iso_19011_2018.
